## ğŸ¯ Objective
- Create forensic images of affected systems to preserve evidence and reduce investigation time  
- Analyze the file system structure of an image file  
- Extract key forensic information including:  
  - File system type  
  - Metadata information  
  - File content information  

## ğŸ§° Tools Used
- **The Sleuth Kit (TSK)** â€“ open-source digital forensic toolkit for disk image analysis and file recovery  

## ğŸ“Œ Procedure

1. Open Command Prompt in:
   `...\The Sleuth Kit (TSK)\bin`

2. Display partition layout:
   mmls path\image-evidence.dd

Identify file system type and OS details:
fsstat path\image-evidence.dd

View image format information:
img_stat path\image-evidence.dd

Examine NTFS metadata files:
-Master File Table (MFT):
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 0

-MFT Mirror:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 1

-Boot sector metadata:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 7

-Volume metadata:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 3

-Attribute Definitions:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 4

-Bitmap metadata:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 6

-Bad Clusters file:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 8

-Security descriptors:
istat -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd 9

List files and directories:
fls -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd

Display inode information for deleted files:
ils -r path\image-evidence.dd

Identify file name by inode number:
ffind -f ntfs path\image-evidence.dd XX

Recover deleted files:
Create a destination folder (YY), then run:
tsk_recover -i raw -e path\image-evidence.dd path\Desktop\YY

ğŸ” Findings
The Master File Table (MFT) maintains an entry for every file and directory in NTFS systems

MFTMirr stores a backup of the initial MFT entries for recovery purposes

The Boot metadata file contains file system boot sector information

The Volume metadata file stores volume label and version details

AttrDef defines attribute types and identifiers

Bitmap tracks allocated and unallocated clusters

BadClus records damaged disk sectors

Secure file stores access control and security descriptors

The -r flag in ils lists only deleted file inodes

ğŸ“š Lessons Learned
The Sleuth Kit is a powerful forensic framework for analyzing disk images

File system metadata provides crucial evidence for reconstruction and timeline analysis

Deleted files can be efficiently identified and recovered from forensic images

Understanding NTFS internal structures significantly enhances forensic investigations
